<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH REFORMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am not impressed by President Bush's campaign reform proposals. If they are 
the measure of the man, he's a lightweight. 
</P>
<P>
He says that abolishing political action committees (PACs) will reduce the 
influence of money in politics (Part I, June 30). Does he believe it? I doubt 
it. He is totally cynical about PACs. Not long ago, he and other Republicans 
touted them for enhancing political participation. Now, they want to get rid of 
them because they give too much to Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
Bush would abolish PACs when it isn't necessary. Why not limit campaign 
spending and specify that within that limit candidates can raise not more than 
20% from PACs? It would reduce their influence while respecting their right to 
participate. More importantly, it would keep campaign spending from spiraling 
out of control, as it does when there are no limits. 
</P>
<P>
Bush has said that he agrees with the Republican Party. There should be no 
limits on spending. A candidate is justified in spending any amount in pursuit 
of public office. I am appalled that he has so little vision. 
</P>
<P>
ERIC STEEL 
</P>
<P>
Oakland 
</P>
</TEXT>
