<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Inventories Rise: Business inventories rose 0.7% in May as sales growth 
stagnated, the Commerce Department said, leading some analysts to predict 
further production cutbacks during the rest of the year. When not accompanied 
by increases in sales, rising inventories often prompt manufacturers to 
decrease production until stockpiled goods are sold, resulting in a loss of 
jobs. The department said inventories held on shelves and back lots climbed to 
a seasonally adjusted $776.9 billion in May after a 0.8% rise in April. The 
pace of business sales, on the other hand, rose a minuscule 0.02% to a 
seasonally adjusted $517.9 billion. Sales had risen 2% in April after holding 
steady in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BUSINESS -- UNITED STATES; INVENTORIES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
