<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOLIDARITY GETS JARUZELSKI VIEW ON PRESIDENCY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES T. POWERS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WARSAW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Communist leader Wojciech Jaruzelski met with Solidarity lawmakers Monday in an 
apparent effort to broaden support for him as a presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
Although Gen. Jaruzelski announced June 30 that he would not be a candidate for 
the presidency, the Communist Party has asked him to reconsider. In recent days 
he has won the support of his own party and one of its Communist allies, the 
United Peasants' Party. 
</P>
<P>
The president is to be chosen by majority vote of the National Assembly (Sejm) 
and the newly created Senate in an election expected Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Jaruzelski withdrew after the Communists' allies in Parliament, the Peasants 
and the Democratic Party, hesitated to give him their support. Although the 
Peasants voted last week to support him, the Democrats have remained on the 
fence. 
</P>
<P>
Solidarity, the independent trade union movement, has 259 votes (46% of the 
total) and could assure Jaruzelski's election, but it is not likely to endorse 
him. Still, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, noting that Poland's internal and 
international situation requires a Communist president, said last week that he 
would cooperate with Jaruzelski if he is elected. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Solidarity's Reluctant Support 
</P>
<P>
Walesa's quasi-endorsement suggested that Solidarity lawmakers, however 
reluctantly, might cast just enough votes to ensure Jaruzelski's election if 
the ill-disciplined Communist coalition fails to hold together. 
</P>
<P>
Jaruzelski has not officially revoked his withdrawal announcement, but he is 
clearly campaigning for the post. 
</P>
<P>
The meeting with the Solidarity lawmakers was closed, but some of the members 
indicated they were not impressed. 
</P>
<P>
"It's the same thing he's been saying for years," said Jozef Lisz, a leader of 
Farmers' Solidarity and a deputy Speaker of the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
Solidarity lawmakers have said in recent weeks that a vote for Jaruzelski would 
be difficult for them to explain to an electorate that blames Jaruzelski for 
the imposition of martial law in 1981 and the suppression of Solidarity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
