<P>
STEALTH BOMBER TAKEN APART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The B-2 stealth bomber will be partially taken apart for inspection and 
analysis after its first successful test flight and should be ready to fly 
again within six weeks, the Pentagon said today. 
</P>
<P>
The $532-million, radar-evading bomber successfully completed its flight Monday 
over the Mojave Desert in Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
"What they will do now is the same thing they do on any test flight of an 
airplane; they will analyze the data," Defense Department spokesman Pete 
Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
"They will also partially take the plane apart and give it a thorough 
inspection and give it additional electronics and avionics tests. They will do 
that inside the hangar before that particular plane flies again," Williams 
said. 
</P>
